ymbolized by long-held stereotypes of the Italian mother. On a larger scale, while the editors and contributors share with previous works on the Italian diaspora a keen interest in the imagining of nations across national borders, here they refocus our attention to the significance of the domestic, particularly the lives of individual men and women, their families, and the communities they loved—and left behind.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 7aHISTORY / Europe / Italy.2bisacsh1 aBaldassar, Loretta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaldassar, Loretta, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBertellini, Giorgio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Tona, Carla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGabaccia, Donna R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGabaccia, Donna R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMcKibben, Carol Lynn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, Pavla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPesman, Ros, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPojmann, Wendy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRieker, Yvonne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStabile, Carol A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWaldron Merithew, Caroline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWessendorf, Susanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311070729840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780